th Colony from the 1620s until his death."],"variants":[{"name":"Brewer","meanings":["English: occupational name for a brewer of beer or ale, from Middle English <i>brewere</i> ‘brewer’ (an agent derivative of Old English <i>brēowan</i> ‘to brew’). Compare   Brewster  .","English (of Norman origin): Anglicized form of French <b>Bruyère</b> (see   Bruyere  ), a habitational name from a place so called in Calvados, France, from Old French <i>bruiere</i> ‘heath’.","Americanized form (translation into English) of Dutch   Brouwer  , German   Brauer   or   Breuer  , etc., all occupational names meaning ‘brewer’."]},{"name":"Bruster","meanings":["English: variant of   Brewster  .","Swiss German: variant of the topographic name   Brust   2, the suffix <i>-er</i> denoting an inhabitant."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament: ‘God is gracious’.  See  <b>John</b> ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705190,"age":11,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"Sir John Brewster I was born in 1279, in Rushmere, Suffolk, England as the son of Edward Brewster II. He had at least 1 son. He died in 1299, in England, at the age of 20, and was buried in Rushmere, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1279–1299":"1279–1299","1299–1325":"1299–1325","1259–Male":"1259–Surnud","1259":"1259","1325":"1325","1279":"1279","1299":"1299","1290":"1290","St. Michael's Churchyard Rushmere, Waveney District, Suffolk, England":"Rushmere, Suffolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"England","Rushmere, Suffolk, England":"Rushmere, Suffolk, England"},"fi":{"1279–1299":"1279–1299","1299–1325":"1299–1325","1259–Male":"1259–Kuollut","1259":"1259","1325":"1325","1279":"1279","1299":"1299","1290":"1290","St. Mi